models_2: Bayesian statistics (more advanced): e.g. multilevel linear and generalized linear models, choosing informative priors, model selection, prior/posterior predictive checks, sensitivity analysis
models_3: Multilevel (also known as hierarchical or random-effects) models. These models do partial pooling of information across participants and are particularly suitable for cases in which we cannot obtain many responses from the same participant (e.g. in children or patients) or for imbalanced datasets.
models_4: Generalized linear models (GLM) for dichotomous variables (e.g. logistic regression)
models_5: Models for ordinal dependent variables (e.g. ordered logit), ordinal independent variables (monotonic effects), or both
models_6: Models for response time data (e.g. inverse-gaussian GLM)
models_7: Generalized additive models (GAM) - these are models that do not assume a priori a specific form (e.g. linear or any other parametric form) of the relationship between predictors and dependent variables
models_8: Dealing with censored, truncated or missing data
extra_1: Programming and doing analyses in R
extra_3: tidyverse (this is an R "dialect" specifically aimed at facilitating data analysis)
extra_4: Maintaining and sharing code and data repositories using Github and OSF
